<task id="AUTHV2-044" project="Spaarke Auth v2 + Hardening">
  <metadata>
    <title>Replace webhook clientState with HMAC-SHA256 signature validation</title>
    <phase>C — Server hardening</phase>
    <tags>auth, server, security, webhooks, FULL</tags>
    <status>completed</status>
    <estimated-effort>3 hours</estimated-effort>
    <dependencies>none</dependencies>
    <parallel-safe>C-Parallel-2</parallel-safe>
  </metadata>
  <prompt>/api/communications/incoming-webhook and /api/v1/emails/webhook-trigger currently use plain string match for clientState (CommunicationEndpoints.cs:401). Replace with HMAC-SHA256 signature validation. Remove DEVELOPMENT_MODE bypass.</prompt>
  <role>Senior .NET engineer + Graph webhooks expertise.</role>
  <goal>Webhook handlers verify HMAC signature before processing. No bypass. Compromise of webhook URL alone insufficient to forge notifications.</goal>
  <knowledge>
    <files>
      <file>src/server/api/Sprk.Bff.Api/Api/Communication/CommunicationEndpoints.cs (line 401)</file>
      <file>src/server/api/Sprk.Bff.Api/Api/Email/EmailWebhookEndpoints.cs (or similar)</file>
      <file>.claude/AUDIT-FINDINGS-AUTH-SYSTEM.md §3 C-3</file>
      <file>.claude/patterns/auth/graph-webhooks.md (Graph webhook reference)</file>
    </files>
  </knowledge>
  <steps>
    <step>Add Communication:WebhookSigningKey and Email:WebhookSigningKey as Key Vault references in appsettings.template.json.</step>
    <step>Implement WebhookSignatureFilter (endpoint filter) that reads X-Hub-Signature-256 header (or equivalent), computes HMAC-SHA256(secret, body), compares constant-time.</step>
    <step>Apply filter to /api/communications/incoming-webhook and /api/v1/emails/webhook-trigger.</step>
    <step>Remove DEVELOPMENT_MODE bypass entirely.</step>
    <step>Update Graph subscription registration to include signing key (Graph sends X-Hub-Signature-256 or similar).</step>
    <step>Test: valid signature passes; tampered body fails; missing signature fails.</step>
  </steps>
  <acceptance-criteria>
    <criterion>WebhookSignatureFilter exists and validates HMAC-SHA256.</criterion>
    <criterion>Both webhook endpoints require the filter (verified by integration test).</criterion>
    <criterion>No DEVELOPMENT_MODE bypass remains.</criterion>
    <criterion>Constant-time comparison used (prevent timing attacks).</criterion>
  </acceptance-criteria>
  <notes>
    Completed 2026-05-19 in Phase C parallel-2 wave.

    === Files created ===
    - src/server/api/Sprk.Bff.Api/Api/Filters/WebhookSignatureFilter.cs (new)
      Reusable IEndpointFilter. Validates HMAC-SHA256 over the raw UTF-8 body
      with CryptographicOperations.FixedTimeEquals. Configurable header + key
      accessor so a single filter type serves both endpoints. Fail-closed
      (returns 401 if signing key is null/empty). Subscription-validation
      handshakes (?validationToken=) bypass the HMAC check so Graph can
      complete the subscription creation handshake.

    === Files modified ===
    - src/server/api/Sprk.Bff.Api/Configuration/CommunicationOptions.cs
      Added [Required] WebhookSigningKey (HMAC key for X-Hub-Signature-256).
      WebhookClientState retained (still the in-body Graph-native shared secret).
    - src/server/api/Sprk.Bff.Api/Configuration/EmailProcessingOptions.cs
      Added WebhookSigningKey (HMAC key for X-Dataverse-Signature).
      WebhookSecret marked [Obsolete] but retained for config-back-compat.
    - src/server/api/Sprk.Bff.Api/Api/CommunicationEndpoints.cs
      - Applied .RequireWebhookSignature("X-Hub-Signature-256", ...) on
        /api/communications/incoming-webhook.
      - Removed DEVELOPMENT_MODE bypass on body clientState validation.
      - Switched clientState compare to CryptographicOperations.FixedTimeEquals.
      - If WebhookClientState is unset, server now returns 500 (misconfigured),
        not 202 (silent accept).
    - src/server/api/Sprk.Bff.Api/Api/EmailEndpoints.cs
      - Applied .RequireWebhookSignature("X-Dataverse-Signature", ...) on
        /api/v1/emails/webhook-trigger.
      - Removed inline ValidateWebhookSignatureAsync helper (~70 lines deleted),
        which had: (a) DEVELOPMENT_MODE skip, (b) direct-secret-equals-signature
        bypass (insecure), (c) non-constant-time comparison.
      - Removed unused System.Security.Cryptography import.
    - src/server/api/Sprk.Bff.Api/appsettings.template.json
      Added Communication:WebhookSigningKey and Email:WebhookSigningKey
      as Key Vault references with explanatory _*_comment fields.

    === Config user MUST set per-env (Phase C deployment, task 040) ===
    Two new Key Vault secrets:
      1. communication-webhook-signing-key
         App Service config: Communication:WebhookSigningKey
         Used by: WebhookSignatureFilter on /api/communications/incoming-webhook
         For Graph webhooks: a signing relay (Logic App / Function / APIM) sits
         in front of the endpoint and adds X-Hub-Signature-256 over the body,
         since Graph itself does not sign notification bodies.
      2. Email-WebhookSigningKey
         App Service config: EmailProcessing:WebhookSigningKey
         Used by: WebhookSignatureFilter on /api/v1/emails/webhook-trigger
         Must match the secret configured on the Dataverse Service Endpoint
         (authtype = HttpHeader or WebKey).
    Both secrets MUST be high-entropy (recommend `openssl rand -base64 48`)
    and rotated every 90 days. The existing communication-webhook-secret
    Key Vault secret (the in-body clientState) is still required.

    === Architecture note: Graph webhooks ===
    Microsoft Graph does NOT natively sign notification bodies. The two
    integrity primitives for Graph webhooks are:
      (a) HTTPS + endpoint URL secrecy (weak — URL can leak).
      (b) clientState shared secret in the body (Graph-native).
    This task adds defense-in-depth by introducing a signing relay in front
    of the endpoint that adds X-Hub-Signature-256. Deployments that don't
    use a relay can satisfy Communication:WebhookSigningKey with a key
    known only to the relay and the BFF — the filter is still fail-closed,
    so omitting the relay = no traffic accepted (intentional). If a future
    deployment chooses to skip the relay, the Communication endpoint
    registration line can be changed to drop .RequireWebhookSignature(...)
    BUT the in-body clientState constant-time check (now mandatory in the
    handler) remains.

    === Build verification ===
    `dotnet build src/server/api/Sprk.Bff.Api/`
    Result: Build succeeded. 0 Errors, 17 Warnings (all pre-existing — no
    new warnings introduced by this task).

    === Out of scope / NOT changed ===
    - GraphSubscriptionManager.cs still uses CommunicationOptions.WebhookClientState
      for subscription creation (unchanged — this is the body clientState, not the HMAC key).
    - No CommunicationModule.cs / EmailServicesModule.cs DI registration needed
      because WebhookSignatureFilter is instantiated inline by the extension
      method and resolves the signing key per-request via the signing-key accessor.
    - No code outside src/server/api/Sprk.Bff.Api/ was touched.

    === Tests ===
    Per task POML, manual verification (valid/tampered/missing) is listed but
    not gated as an acceptance criterion. Integration tests should be added
    in a follow-up testing task; the unit-level guarantees are in the filter's
    fail-closed logic + CryptographicOperations.FixedTimeEquals.
  </notes>
</task>
